ing-peacock\",\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"tool_use_id\":\"toolu_015QmTWyKJenNRvrG5eKrQU3\",\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"content\":\"     1→# Implement Command\\n     2→\\n     3→Build the agent Go package using E2E-driven development. E2E tests are the primary spec — unit tests are written *after* each E2E test passes to lock in behavior.\\n     4→\\n     5→## Prerequisites\\n     6→\\n     7→- The research command's one-pager at `cmd/entire/cli/agent/$AGENT_SLUG/AGENT.md`\\n     8→- The E2E test runner already added (from `write-tests` command)\\n     9→- If no one-pager exists, read the agent's docs and ask the user about hook events, transcript format, and config\\n    10→\\n    11→## Procedure\\n    12→\\n    13→### Step 1: Read Implementation Guide\\n    14→\\n    15→Read these files thoroughly before writing any code:\\n    16→\\n    17→1. `docs/architecture/agent-guide.md` — Authoritative implementation guide with code templates. Read thoroughly.\\n    18→2. `docs/architecture/agent-integration-checklist.md` — Validation criteria for completeness.\\n    19→3. `cmd/entire/cli/agent/agent.go` — Read to find the exact `Agent` interface and all optional interfaces.\\n    20→4. `cmd/entire/cli/agent/event.go` — Read to find `EventType` constants and shared parsing helpers.\\n    21→\\n    22→### Step 2: Read Reference Implementation\\n    23→\\n    24→Read `cmd/entire/cli/agent/$AGENT_SLUG/AGENT.md` (the one-pager from the research phase) for the agent's hook mechanism, transcript format, and config structure.\\n    25→\\n    26→Run `Glob(\\\"cmd/entire/cli/agent/*/\\\")` to find all existing agent packages. Check the one-pager's \\\"Hook Mechanism\\\" and \\\"Gaps & Limitations\\\" sections to pick the best reference — choose an agent with a similar hook mechanism to your target. Read all `*.go` files (skip `*_test.go` on first pass) in the chosen reference.\\n    27→\\n    28→### Step 3: Create Bare-Minimum Compiling Package\\n    29→\\n    30→Create the agent package directory and stub out every required interface method so the project compiles.\\n    31→\\n    32→```\\n    33→cmd/entire/cli/agent/$AGENT_SLUG/\\n    34→```\\n    35→\\n    36→**What to create:**\\n    37→\\n    38→1. **`${AGENT_SLUG}.go`** — Struct definition, `init()` with `agent.Register(agent.AgentName(\\\"$AGENT_SLUG\\\"), New)`, and stub implementations for all `Agent` interface methods (Name, Type, Description, IsPreview, DetectPresence, ProtectedDirs, GetSessionDir, ResolveSessionFile, ReadTranscript, ChunkTranscript, ReassembleTranscript).\\n    39→2. **`types.go`** — Hook input struct(s) with JSON tags matching the one-pager's \\\"Hook input (stdin JSON)\\\" section.\\n    40→3. **`lifecycle.go`** — Stub `ParseHookEvent()` that returns `nil, nil` for all inputs. Use the one-pager's \\\"Hook names\\\" table for the native hook name → Entire EventType mapping.\\n    41→4. **`hooks.go`** — Stub `InstallHooks()`, `UninstallHooks()`, `AreHooksInstalled()` that return nil/false. Use the one-pager's \\\"Config file\\\" and \\\"Hook registration\\\" sections for the config path and format.\\n    42→5. **`transcript.go`** — Stub `TranscriptAnalyzer` methods if the one-pager's \\\"Transcript\\\" section indicates the agent supports transcript analysis. Use the one-pager for transcript location and format.\\n    43→\\n    44→**Wire up blank imports:**\\n    45→\\n    46→- Add `_ \\\"github.com/entireio/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/$AGENT_SLUG\\\"` to `cmd/entire/cli/agent/hooks_cmd.go`\\n    47→- Add the agent to the config map in `cmd/entire/cli/agent/config.go`\\n    48→\\n    49→**Verify compilation:**\\n    50→\\n    51→```bash\\n    52→mise run fmt && mise run lint && mise run test\\n    53→```\\n    54→\\n    55→Everything must pass before proceeding. Fix any issues.\\n    56→\\n    57→**Standing instruction for Steps 4-12:** If you need agent-specific information (hook format, transcript location, config structure), chec