t the native hook name Claude Code uses. The real EventType should be `TurnEnd` or `SessionEnd` depending on context, and looking at event.go, there's no `Stop` EventType at all. This same mistake appears in the unit test section and continues through Step 5, where it lists the 4 basic events to handle.\\n\\nThe pattern is consistent: `UserPromptSubmit` should be `TurnStart`, `SubagentTaskStart`/`SubagentTaskEnd` should be `SubagentStart`/`SubagentEnd`, and `Stop` needs to map to the correct EventType. This is a high-severity issue because it means the implementation guide is using Claude Code-specific hook names instead of the canonical EventType names that should actually be used.\\n\\nNow looking at the identifier model, I'm seeing that `AGENT_SLUG` is overloaded across multiple contexts. It's defined as a lowercase slug for file paths, but it's actually being used for Go package names (which can't have hyphens), E2E agent names (which can have hyphens), environment variable filtering, and the Entire agent registry—and these don't all align with each other. The Go package name and the E2E agent name are fundamentally different identifiers being conflated under one term. The issue is clear now—the E2E agent filter would be `gemini` but it's actually `gemini-cli`. With `AGENT_SLUG=claude-code`, I run into the same problem: hyphens aren't valid in Go package names, yet the actual package is `claudecode`. This confirms the parameter is genuinely ambiguous across different agents. Claude Code and OpenCode work by coincidence because their naming happens to align, but Gemini exposes the real problem with three distinct identifiers (`geminicli` for the package, `gemini` for the registry, `gemini-cli` for E2E), making the skill produce incorrect code for agents without 1:1 name mapping.\\n\\nThe skill also assumes a hook-only implementation model. The documentation mandates creating `hooks.go` with specific functions and the test suite exercises hook installation, but the codebase actually defines a `FileWatcher` interface as an alternative approach. If someone tries to integrate an agent like Aider that uses file watching instead of hooks, the skill would force them down the hook path with stubs that won't actually work—this limitation isn't declared anywhere.\\n\\nThere's also a contradiction in the guidance: the skill lists the agent integration checklist as a shared Architecture Reference, but the researcher instructions explicitly forbid reading it. It's a real conflict but low-impact since the researcher doesn't actually need the checklist to do their work.\\n\\nNow I'm evaluating the proposed fixes against each finding. Replacing the stale method list with the actual checklist would solve the root cause of the first issue, adding a glossary would clarify the hook naming confusion, splitting the AGENT_SLUG parameter would reduce ambiguity though it adds some complexity, an early branch for HookSupport versus FileWatcher would streamline the flow, and aligning the checklist reference would resolve the guidance conflict. I'll draft the implementation plan now.\",\"signature\":\"\"}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":1,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":2059,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":92665,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":2059},\"output_tokens\":8,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"inference_geo\":\"not_available\"}},\"requestId\":\"req_011CYXhEJZeBNwjeWwvtFjWG\",\"type\":\"assistant\",\"uuid\":\"76f76da4-f6e3-4fbf-a1cf-4cc126abf83f\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-27T01:20:27.851Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"76f76da4-f6e3-4fbf-a1cf-4cc126abf83f\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alisha/Projects/wt/kiro-oneshot\",\"sessionId\":\"d044e6bf-a45b-461e-905a-21fb10294c11\",\"version\":\"2.1.61\",\"gitBranch\":\"alisha/kiro-oneshot\",\"slug\":\"snuggly-beaming-peacock\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01VDHdPazT